<br>
&quot;Yes mother, I am.&quot; came a tired reply.<br>
<br>
&quot;Come dear.  Tragedy has stricken your family.  Your mother and brothers have been slain!  We must ride swiftly through the woods, using the darkness as our shield.&quot;<br>
<br>
Raloth leaped out of bed with the speed of an enraged cougar on the hunt.  He did not realize right away that there was no one in his room.  Quickly he ran out into the living area of his family's modest hut, in search of the source of the voice that sounded strangely like that of his mother.   What he found instead was an Orc Scout rumaging through their belongings ... apparently the scout had decided to take a few things for himself before his posse arrived.   Either way, Raloth knew that whatever time he had before the others arrived was short to say the least.<br>
<br>
With the agility of a cat and the strength of a lion, Raloth leaped into the air and landed a Cresent kick up against the side of the Orc's head.  Stunned, the beast fell back a few steps, moaning and groaning something Raloth could not understand.  Quickly the Orc regained his bearings, and unsheathed a rusty-looking longsword, and took a swipe at Raloth's mid-section.  <br>
<br>
Raloth was simply to quick for the weaker Orc, and the sword hit nothing but the humid air.  The miss caused the Orc to fall to the side slightly, and Raloth took advantage of the situation.  A lightning fast uppercut smashed the teeth of the gnoll straight up into the ridge of its mouth.  Blood and broken teeth gushed out like a river, and the Orc let lose a howl of pain so terrible, so painful, that even Raloth paused for a moment.<br>
<br>
He stood looking at the shattered face of his blood-enemy.  He knew this particular one was not responsible for the death of his mother.  Something inside his soul told him that.  But Raloth new that if it was left alone to live that it might do something the same to another innocent victim.<br>
<br>
With a calculated move, Raloth leaped into the air, and smashed his knee into the shattered jaw of the wounded Orc.  More teeth fragments shot out of the beasts mouth, and the teeth that were lodged at the top of its jaw were shoved into its brain.  The beast dropped, lifeless and bloody.<br>
<br>
Raloth stared at the Orc's corpse for a few minutes. until he heard the noises outside.  He ran to the window and could see the movements of more Orcs in the deeper shadows, their blood red eyes gave away their location.<br>
<br>
Fuming, yet resolute and strangely calm, Raloth took a few steps to the door.  He could count six of them within eyesight, but he knew in reality that there was at least another four lurking around in the shadows behind them.  He did not care.  His mind was clear and focused.  He only sought one, and for some strange reason he even knew which one it would be.  The others ... well ... they were just in the way.<br>
<br>
Just as Raloth opened the door, chaos let loose its reign upon his once humble and quiet dwelling place ...<br>
<br>
<br>
